==== From Time Distortion to Substitution: The Mirror Rule

As developed in @sec:time-distortion, the swing of a duplet can be understood as a distortion of time — a transfer function $f$ that warps absolute clock time into functional musical time — and this distortion co-induces, on any subdivision structurally constrained by the duplet, a paired distortion $g$ satisfying $g = f^(-1)$ on a simple reading. The paired distortion acts on the triplet emergent from the duplet's 2:1 ratio, and the two swings carry opposite groove balances. The present section develops the consequence of this coupling when the relation between the two levels is read symbolically — as an operation that takes one word on the alphabet ${L, S}$ to another. A substitution rule emerges without having to be posited, and this rule turns out to be the symbolic writing of the mirror effect of Section 3.2.2.

The elementary case is immediate. The duplet swung at 100% is the word $S L$: a short followed by a long, with total absolute length $3$. The triplet inscribed in the same pulse, swung to its mirror position, is the word $L S S$: a long followed by two shorts, with total absolute length $4$. The two words share their onsets at three points — the beginning of the pulse, the internal boundary where the short of the duplet meets the long, and the end of the pulse — and the swinging of each layer is structurally tied to the swinging of the other through the coupling of $f$ and $g$. Read letter by letter, the correspondence between $S L$ and $L S S$ is the rule:
$
S arrow.r L, quad L arrow.r S S.
$
Applied to $S L$, it produces $sigma(S) sigma(L) = L dot S S = L S S$, precisely the mirror-swung triplet. The substitution rule is not an independent discovery; it is the symbolic notation of the mirror effect already established in Section 3.2.2, now written as an operation that takes one word to another.

Having extracted the rule, the natural question is whether it can be _iterated_ — whether applying it again and again to its own output produces a coherent infinite structure, a genuine fractal rhythm in the sense outlined in the introduction to this sub-chapter. Compute the successive iterations starting from $S L$:
$
sigma^1(S L) & = L S S \
sigma^2(S L) & = sigma(L) sigma(S) sigma(S) = S S dot L dot L = S S L L \
sigma^3(S L) & = sigma(S) sigma(S) sigma(L) sigma(L) = L dot L dot S S dot S S = L L S S S S \
sigma^4(S L) & = sigma(L) sigma(L) sigma(S) sigma(S) sigma(S) sigma(S) = S S S S L L L L
$
The pattern is immediately visible. At every iteration, the letters bunch together: all the $L$s on one side, all the $S$s on the other. The word $L L S S S S$ is not a rhythm in any meaningful sense; it is a block of two long events followed by a block of four short events. The word $S S S S L L L L$ is worse: four compressed pulses followed by four expanded pulses, with no interleaving whatsoever. The rule drives its output toward configurations that are maximally segregated, with no mixture of letters at any intermediate position.

The absolute lengths of the successive words trace the same conclusion from a different angle. In absolute units with $L = 2$ and $S = 1$, the lengths of $S L$, $L S S$, $S S L L$, $L L S S S S$, $S S S S L L L L$ are $3, 4, 6, 8, 12$, continuing as $16, 24, 32, 48, 64, dots$. The ratios of consecutive lengths are $4/3, 6/4 = 3/2, 8/6 = 4/3, 12/8 = 3/2, dots$ — strictly alternating between $3:2$ and $4:3$, and never venturing outside the harmonic region bounded by $2:1$. Translated into interval language, the rule produces only _octaves_, _fifths_, and _fourths_ — the intervals of Pythagorean harmonic structure, with no access to thirds, sixths, or any harmonic ratios involving higher primes. The iteration is a ping-pong between $f$ and $g$, between duplet and triplet, between two subdivision rates, and it never escapes this narrow corridor.

This is the same harmonic poverty that characterises the Western metric system, to which the mirror rule is closely related. The Western system of note durations — whole, half, quarter, eighth, sixteenth, and so on down — is generated by the even more elementary substitution $L arrow.r L L$, $S arrow.r S S$: each symbol is replaced by two copies of itself. This rule is homogeneous in the extreme, but its structure is monotonous: it produces only doublings, only ratios of $2:1$, only octaves. No swing is possible within this system, because no inequality is ever introduced. The mirror rule $S arrow.r L$, $L arrow.r S S$ is one step above the Western system — it does introduce inequality, it does produce the swing $S L$ from $L L$ — but it remains trapped in the same harmonic neighbourhood, producing only $2:1$, $3:2$, and $4:3$ ratios under iteration. The increment of structure is real but modest: from no swing at all to a rigid alternation between two swing configurations, with no possibility of richer rhythmic material at deeper levels.

The failure of the mirror rule as a fractal generator can be made precise through the informal notion of _entropy_. For a finite word on the binary alphabet ${L, S}$, call the entropy a measure of how well the two letters are interleaved across the word. A word in which shorts and longs alternate regularly — $S L S L S L dots$ — has high entropy: the letters are maximally distributed. A word in which all the shorts precede all the longs — $S S S S L L L L$ — has low entropy: the letters are maximally segregated. The intuition is that high-entropy words are rhythmically rich, while low-entropy words are rhythmically poor. This informal notion of entropy is, up to a sign, the reciprocal of the potential energy introduced in Section 3.1.3: a word whose onsets cluster far from uniform spacing carries high potential energy and low entropy; a word whose onsets are evenly distributed carries low potential energy and high entropy.#footnote[A formal treatment of the entropy of finite and infinite words, along with its relation to the Fisher information metric and to the topological entropy of substitution dynamical systems, is given in Book IV. The informal notion used in the present section is sufficient for the argument at hand.]

The iterations of the mirror rule drive the entropy of the output monotonically toward its minimum. Every application of $sigma$ doubles the clustering of its input: wherever there is an $L$, it becomes $S S$ (a cluster of two shorts); wherever there is an $S$, it becomes $L$ (a single long, but one that will itself become a cluster at the next iteration). The rule has no mechanism for interleaving the two letters — no $sigma(S)$ that would introduce an $L$ alongside itself, no $sigma(L)$ that would mix shorts and longs within a single block. Structurally, the rule operates with only two states, and the iteration is a permanent oscillation between them. That oscillation is what the alternation of $f$ and $g$ looks like at the symbolic level, and it is the root cause of the harmonic poverty observed above.

The conclusion is sobering but structurally productive. The mirror rule of Section 3.2.2 is musically perfect at a single level: it generates the swung triplet from the swung duplet, and preserves synchronicity across the entire morphing range. More than that: the consistency condition on the long–short ratio across one application of the rule, $r = 2/r$, yields $r = sqrt(2)$, in exact agreement with the tempering argument of Section 3.2.3 that identified $sqrt(2)$ as the meantone of the rhythmic domain — the ratio at which the balanced 50% swing position sits. The rule and the tempering are two readings of the same structural fact. But the rule, iterated, does not manifest this ratio in the distribution of its output: the words it produces have the right asymptotic counts of $L$s and $S$s, but the letters are clustered rather than interleaved. The mirror rule has the right _ratio_ but not the right _distribution_. It is not a fractal rule. Iterated, it collapses into clustered blocks whose internal structure is harmonically poor and rhythmically inert.

If the programme outlined in the introduction to this sub-chapter is to succeed — a substitution rule that preserves the swing feel under indefinite iteration, producing a genuinely fractal rhythmic object at every scale — a different rule is needed, one that breaks out of the harmonic neighbourhood to which the mirror is confined, and whose consistency condition selects an irrational ratio with the structural depth to govern indefinite subdivision. What such a rule must look like, and what irrational proportion emerges from it, is the subject of the next section.


==== The Swinging Substitution: Fibonacci and the Golden Ratio

The failure of the mirror rule has a diagnosis that points toward its remedy. The rule $S arrow.r L$, $L arrow.r S S$ takes a long and replaces it with two shorts — two shorts that sit side by side, unmodified, at the deeper subdivision level. This is a conceptual slip. If the object under study is the swing, then a long that resolves into two equal shorts at the next level has lost its swing at that level. The subdivision has been refined, but the refinement itself is _straight_. It belongs to a different domain — the domain of the _elementary substitution_ $L arrow.r L L$, $S arrow.r S S$ that generates the nested doublings of the Western note-value system. The mirror rule shares with this elementary substitution the same structural limitation: whatever it produces at a finer level is no longer swung. It is, in the end, a straight subdivision dressed in swung symbols.

The remedy, once stated, is evident. If the rule is to remain within the domain of swing, it must swing the substituted material as well. Each long must be replaced not by two straight shorts, but by a _swung_ pair — a long followed by a short, or equivalently a short followed by a long. The rule becomes:
$
S arrow.r L, quad L arrow.r L S.
$
This small modification is, structurally, a large change. The pattern $L L$ at a given level no longer refines into $S S S S$ at the next, but into $L S L S$ — two swung duplets concatenated. Each long has become a miniature swung duplet, and the swing has propagated from one level to the next without interruption. The word is swung all the way down.

Before pursuing the consequences, it is worth noting that the rule just written down is, in the combinatorial literature, the canonical _Fibonacci morphism_, and the infinite word it generates — the limit $sigma^infinity(L)$ of its iterations — is the classical Fibonacci word, or _rabbit sequence_, the most studied Sturmian word of the field.#footnote[See @sec:state-of-research for references: Noll 2008; Allouche & Johnson 2018; Berstel 2007; OEIS A003849. The Fibonacci morphism is a paradigmatic case in combinatorics on words, and its musical appearances — in Nørgård's infinity series analysis by Shallit (2005, 2017), in Tom Johnson's _Narayana's Cows_, in Noll's treatment of modes — are documented in the state-of-research.] This identification — musical rule derived from a structural constraint on swing, mathematical object developed independently in combinatorics — is one of the surprising fruits of the present approach. The rule was not borrowed from the mathematical literature and applied to rhythm; it emerged from a musical requirement, and only then was recognised as an object already known for its exceptional properties.

Compute the successive iterations starting from $L$:
$
sigma^0(L) & = L \
sigma^1(L) & = L S \
sigma^2(L) & = L S dot L = L S L \
sigma^3(L) & = L S dot L dot L S = L S L L S \
sigma^4(L) & = L S dot L dot L S dot L S dot L = L S L L S L S L \
sigma^5(L) & = L S dot L dot L S dot L S dot L dot L S dot L dot L S = L S L L S L S L L S L L S
$
The lengths of these words are $1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, dots$ — the _Fibonacci numbers_, each the sum of the two preceding. The number of $L$s and $S$s in each word also follows Fibonacci: in $sigma^n(L)$, there are $F_n$ longs and $F_(n-1)$ shorts, where $F_n$ denotes the $n$-th Fibonacci number. Unlike the mirror rule, whose iterates alternated between clustered configurations, the iterates of the swinging substitution exhibit _interleaving_: shorts and longs alternate through the word without forming pure blocks of either letter. The distribution is homogeneous at every scale.

The irrational proportion governing this rule emerges, as in the mirror case, from a _consistency condition_ — the requirement that the long-to-short ratio $r = L/S$ be preserved by a single application of the rule. Since $sigma(L) = L S$ has length $L + S = (1 + 1/r) dot L$ in absolute terms, and $sigma(S) = L$ has length $L$, the ratio after substitution is:
$
r_"new" = frac(|sigma(L)|, |sigma(S)|) = frac(L + S, L) = 1 + frac(1, r).
$
The consistency requirement $r_"new" = r$ yields the quadratic equation:
$
r = 1 + frac(1, r), quad "or equivalently" quad r^2 - r - 1 = 0,
$
whose positive root is the _golden ratio_:
$
r = phi = frac(1 + sqrt(5), 2) approx 1.618.
$
The swing that satisfies this rule, at which longs and shorts stand in golden ratio to one another, lies between the maximally swung duplet (100%, ratio $2$) and the straight duplet (0%, ratio $1$). Converted into the swing percentage used throughout this work, the golden-ratio swing corresponds to approximately $69.4%$#footnote[Using the conversion $"swing %" = ((r - 1) / (2 - 1)) times 100% = (r - 1) times 100%$, one obtains $(phi - 1) times 100% approx 61.8%$ in the long-leading convention. In the short-leading convention used in "\#ref" the result is the complementary value. Full computation in @sec:math-fibonacci-swing.] — a position lying between the 50% swing ($sqrt(2)$, meantone of Section 3.2.3) and the 100% swing. This places the golden ratio swing, in the rhythmic continuum, in the neighbourhood of the triplet side of the jazz swing zone, but distinct from both the meantone balance and the 2:1 maximum.

The consistency condition that yielded $phi$ should be read carefully. It is not a limit reached asymptotically by the iteration, nor a statistical property emerging from long words. It is an _a priori structural requirement_: for the rule to produce a coherent swing at every level, the ratio must satisfy a condition that admits only one positive solution. The irrational number $phi$ is not a curiosity that happens to appear; it is the unique proportion that makes the swinging substitution possible as a self-similar structure. In this sense, $phi$ is to the swinging substitution what $sqrt(2)$ is to the mirror rule, and what the upcoming ternary extension will associate with the plastic ratio $rho$: each irrational proportion is the consistency condition of a specific substitution rule, the _only_ ratio at which that rule can be iterated without breaking the swing at some level.

Two further observations establish the contrast with the mirror rule. First, the entropy of the Fibonacci word is maximal, in the precise sense that the number of distinct substrings of length $n$ that appear in it is exactly $n + 1$ — the lowest possible complexity for an aperiodic infinite sequence. This is the defining property of _Sturmian words_, and the Fibonacci word is the canonical example.#footnote[For formal definitions and proofs, see @sec:math-sturmian-fibonacci. The property is equivalent, under a suitable reading, to the condition that the Fibonacci word be _balanced_: for any two substrings of the same length, the number of $L$s differs by at most one.] Where the mirror rule drove entropy toward its minimum, the swinging substitution sits at the theoretical maximum. The letters interleave with the tightest constraint that still allows aperiodicity. No rhythmic structure on a binary alphabet can distribute its elements more uniformly.

Second, the harmonic neighbourhood of $phi$ lies outside the Pythagorean corridor. The successive ratios of Fibonacci numbers $2/1, 3/2, 5/3, 8/5, 13/8, 21/13, dots$ approach $phi$ from alternating directions, but none of them equals $phi$. Each ratio is a rational approximation, and $phi$ itself is irrational and, more strongly, the _worst-approximable_ real number in the sense of continued fractions — its continued fraction expansion is $[1; 1, 1, 1, dots]$, the simplest possible, which is precisely why it resists rational approximation more obstinately than any other irrational. Musically, this places the golden-ratio swing in a harmonic position that no combination of octaves, fifths, and fourths can ever capture. It is a new neighbourhood, and the rule that generates it opens a region of the rhythmic continuum that the mirror rule — and a fortiori the elementary substitution — could not reach.

The swinging substitution is therefore the first genuine fractal rule of this sub-chapter. It preserves the swing at every level of iteration; it satisfies a consistency condition that selects a unique irrational proportion; it produces an infinite word of maximal entropy; and it occupies a harmonic neighbourhood distinct from the pythagorean region in which the mirror is confined. Whether it is the only such rule on the binary alphabet, or whether other binary substitution rules satisfying analogous consistency conditions can be found — and what irrational proportions those rules would select — is the question of the next section.